+      {
+        rank: 2,
+        title: "Wynand Fockink — the kopstootje masterclass",
+        description:
+          "Down an alley behind Dam Square, a 1679 tasting house unchanged in method: dozens of house-distilled genevers and liqueurs, served in tulip glasses filled to a trembling meniscus — protocol demands the kopstootje ('little headbutt'): hands behind back, bow to the bar, first sip taken stooped. Standing room only, early-evening hours, liqueur names like poetry ('Bride's Tears' carries gold flakes). The attached distillery shop sends bottles home. Twenty minutes here teaches more Dutch culture than three museums.",
+      },
+      {
+        rank: 3,
+        title: "In 't Aepjen — drinking among the monkeys",
+        description:
+          "One of the city's two surviving wooden houses (1519) hosts a bar whose name — 'In the Monkeys' — recalls sailors paying tabs with primates from the East Indies; carved apes still oversee proceedings. Zeedijk's location stitches it to the harbor's rough history, now calmed into atmospheric candlelight and jazz Sundays. It's a working local despite the postcard credentials: genever list deep, tourists welcomed but outnumbered at the right hours. The Schreierstoren ('weeping tower') and old-harbor walk bracket it perfectly.",
+      },
+      {
+        rank: 4,
+        title: "Café de Dokter — the smallest, darkest perfect",
+        description:
+          "Allegedly Amsterdam's smallest café: one room of surgeon-founded heritage (1798, hence the name) behind Kalverstraat's retail roar — smoked sausage, dusty bottles, candle stubs on barrels, a proprietor pouring with deliberation. Capacity maybe twenty; intimacy non-negotiable. It distills the brown-café thesis: time moves differently where chandeliers have soot. Weekday late afternoons grant seats; weekends require standing diplomacy. Pair with Begijnhof's hidden courtyard around the corner for the full secret-city hour.",
+      },
+      {
+        rank: 5,
+        title: "Proeflokaal A. van Wees / De Drie Fleschjes — the deep cuts",
+        description:
+          "The genever constellation continues: De Drie Fleschjes (1650) behind the Nieuwe Kerk, its wall of private casks marked with regulars' names across generations; Van Wees's distillery taproom defending hundred-proof tradition. Tasting strategy: jonge (lighter, modern) versus oude (maltier, the historic style) — order one of each with a beer between, and let the barman narrate. These rooms close early (genever is an evening-opener, not a closer) — schedule the ritual at 5 p.m. like the merchants always did.",
+      },
+      {
