+        title: "Van Gogh Museum — chronology as heartbreak",
+        description:
+          "The world's deepest Van Gogh holdings, hung as biography: potato-dark Brabant beginnings, Paris color conversion, Arles sunflowers and wheatfields, the Auvers finale — letters threading the descent and transcendence. Tickets are timed-entry only and sell out days ahead (book the moment plans firm; Friday evening openings are the calm slot). Ninety dense minutes suffice; the audio guide's letter readings justify themselves. Exit understanding the sunflowers were never decoration — they were arguments for joy made under siege.",
+      },
+      {
+        rank: 3,
+        title: "Anne Frank House — the queue that matters",
+        description:
+          "The secret annex behind the bookcase: preserved emptiness (Otto Frank insisted the rooms stay unfurnished), pencil growth-marks on wallpaper, the diary itself concluding the descent. Tickets release online only, weeks ahead, evaporating in minutes — calendar the release date or accept defeat; there is no door queue anymore. Evening slots run quietest. Allow the Westerkerk bells (Anne's documented comfort) to close the visit from the canal outside. No museum visit in Europe carries more weight per square meter; plan nothing demanding after.",
+      },
+      {
+        rank: 4,
+        title: "Stedelijk — the modern counterargument",
+        description:
+          "Museumplein's third pillar ('the bathtub' extension announces it): Mondrian's evolution from trees to grids, CoBrA's wild children, Malevich depth, design floors where your furniture's ancestors pose. It absorbs the Rijksmuseum's overflow gracefully — same-day entry usually survives, crowds thin, benches contemplative. The collection rehangs keep repeat visits honest. Pair with the Moco's Banksy-bait next door only if irony amuses; the Stedelijk is the serious modern hour. The plein's lawn between museums hosts the decompression picnic.",
+      },
+      {
+        rank: 5,
+        title: "Rembrandt House & the Jordaan house-museums",
+        description:
+          "The house Rembrandt bought at fame's peak and lost to bankruptcy: reconstructed studio with daily etching demonstrations, the cabinet of curiosities he hoarded (the inventory from his insolvency enabled the restoration's accuracy), paint-grinding lessons in period light. It humanizes the Rijksmuseum's god. Extend the register: Museum Van Loon's canal-house grandeur, Willet-Holthuysen's preserved interiors — the merchant city's domestic theater. These intimate rooms, bookable same-day, often outlast the blockbusters in memory. The Jordaan's hofjes (almshouse courtyards) continue the quiet thread free.",
